What is data wrangling

  • Wikipedia: “The process of transforming and mapping data from one”raw data form into another format with the intent of making it more appropriate and valuable for a variety of downstream purposes such as analytics.

  • Layman: data transformation to make it easily accessible and readable.

The dplyr package

Typically we need to explore and prepare data for analysis:

  • create summary statistics for variables and individuals.
  • individuals that do not meet certain criteria need to be removed.
  • create new variables.
  • do multiple things at the same time, eg. subsetting, creating, extracting.

dplyr provide a clean and nice syntax to perform these!

Commonly-used dplyr functions

“verb” functions in dplyr:

  • select()
  • filter()
  • mutate()
  • summarize()
  • group_by()

Installation

library(tidyverse) # automatically load dplyr

# or install dplyr
install.packages("dplyr")
library(dplyr)

select(): subsetting data column wise

  • select() allows you to select columns (or variables) in a data frame.
  • select(x, y) means selecting variable y from data frame x.
  • Note: y can be a vector of column names or numerical positions in the data frame.

select(): in action

select(diamonds, carat, price) # extract carat and price

filter(): subsetting data row wise

  • filter() allows you to extract rows that meet some logical criteria.
  • filter(x, y): extract the rows of x where y is TRUE.

filter(): in action

filter(diamonds, price <= 2000) # filter diamonds with price under 2000

mutate(): change/create a variable

  • mutate(x, y=args): add a column y to data frame x, where y = args. If y already exists, then replace y with y = args.
  • You can change/create multiple variables using one pass of mutate().

mutate(): creating a variable

mutate(diamonds_4c,
       carat_squared = carat^2,
       carat_cubed = carat^3)

summarize(): Summarize the data

  • summarize() creates a new table of summary statistics (Maps a vector to a scalar).
  • summarize(x, y = f(z)): Apply f to the variable z in x and call it y.
  • Some example functions: sum(z), mean(z), median(z), min(z), max(z).
  • Allows user-defined functions.
  • summarise() works as well.

summarize(): in action

summarize(diamonds, avg_price = mean(price))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   avg_price
##       <dbl>
## 1     3933.

summarize(): in action

  • allows user-defined functions (takes a vector and returns a scalar)
ssq <- function(x){
  return(sum(x^2))
}
summarize(diamonds, ssq_price = ssq(price))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##       ssq_price
##           <dbl>
## 1 1692758457943

summarize(): in action

  • can output multiple summaries!
summarize(diamonds,
          mean_price = mean(price),
          median_price = median(price))
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   mean_price median_price
##        <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1      3933.         2401

summarize(): summarize the data

  • summarize() takes a vector and return a scalar value and thus disregards other variables in the data.
  • Sometimes, we are interested in looking at group-specific summaries.
  • E.g: Average price based on cut.

group_by(): group the data

  • Now any functions we apply will be based on the grouping, eg. summarize(), filter(), mutate(), etc.

group_by(): in action

diamonds_cut <- group_by(diamonds, cut)
summarize(diamonds_cut,
          mean_price = mean(price),
          median_price = median(price))
## # A tibble: 5  3
##   cut       mean_price median_price
##   <ord>          <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1 Fair           4359.        3282 
## 2 Good           3929.        3050.
## 3 Very Good      3982.        2648 
## 4 Premium        4584.        3185 
## 5 Ideal          3458.        1810

Applying more than one transformation

  • Oftentimes, we want to apply multiple transformation to the data, eg. filter(), mutate(), etc.
  • dplyr provides an easier and cleaner way to apply multiple transformations through pipe function!

The pipe function %>%

The pipe function %>% (or |>) is essentially a transformation of a data frame to another data frame.

Think about it as an assembly line!

Excercises (revisited)

diamonds_cut <- group_by(diamonds, cut)
summarize(diamonds_cut,
          mean_price = mean(price),
          median_price = median(price))
## # A tibble: 5  3
##   cut       mean_price median_price
##   <ord>          <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1 Fair           4359.        3282 
## 2 Good           3929.        3050.
## 3 Very Good      3982.        2648 
## 4 Premium        4584.        3185 
## 5 Ideal          3458.        1810

Exercise (revisited): use pipe function %>%

diamonds %>% 
  group_by(cut) %>% 
  summarize(mean_price = mean(price),
            median_price = median(price))
## # A tibble: 5  3
##   cut       mean_price median_price
##   <ord>          <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1 Fair           4359.        3282 
## 2 Good           3929.        3050.
## 3 Very Good      3982.        2648 
## 4 Premium        4584.        3185 
## 5 Ideal          3458.        1810

Other useful functions

  • merge data sets: inner_join(), left_join(), right_join(), anti_join(), etc.
  • pivot_longer() and pivor_wider(): converts data from wide to long and vice versa.

HPC

HPC (high performance computing) aggregates the resources from individual computers (nodes) into a cluster that works together to perform advanced, specialized computing jobs.

HPC at USC

CARC: Center for Advanced Research Computing

  • https://www.carc.usc.edu/
  • https://www.carc.usc.edu/user-information/user-guides/hpc-basics/discovery-resources

Provides workshop and weekly office hours

CARC computing resource

  • Login node (Head node)
  • Compute node wired together (~500), including CPU and GPU nodes
  • Disk array and file servers
  • Slurm job scheduler
  • Discovery (free) and Endeavour (paid by PI) cluster

Accessing CARC system

PI can add a member to a project

Username: USC NetID (eg. zzhang39)

Network requirment

  • On campus: connect to “USC secure wireless”
  • Off campus: get your device connected to USC VPN

Connecting to Discovery login node

Method 1: Secure shell command line interface (highly recommended)

  • On Mac: Terminal
  • On Windows: OpenSSH, Putty, etc
ssh <username>@discovery.usc.edu

Connecting to Discovery login node

Method 2: Use OnDemand interface

https://www.carc.usc.edu/user-guides/carc-ondemand/ondemand-overview

Navigate the system

private to yourself:

  • home directory: /home1/<username>
  • scratch directories: /scratch1/<username>

private to a group:

  • /project/<pi_username_id>

Commonly used commands

pwd # print working dir
cd  # change dir

ls -lh # list files
less   # go through a file forward and backward
cat    # print to screen
head   # print the top 10 rows
tail   # print the last 10 rows

mkdir  # create a new dir
touch  # create an empty file
mv     # move file to another dir; or change file/dir name
cp     # copy files
rm     # remove files; WARNING: be careful with this

man    # look at manuals for each command

Request interactive node

In shell:

salloc --time=1:00:00 --mem=8Gb

Please DO NOT run heavy task on login node!
